atus>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/E01657X/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>Social dilemmas are scenarios in which individuals have to decide between a choice that is rational on an individual level and one that is rational at a collective level. An example would be the use of public transport, taking the car (comfortable, convenient etc, but cause congestion) or taking the bus (uncomfortable, inconvenient, but reduces congestion). The collectively rational choice is defined as a cooperative choice and the individually rational choice as a non-cooperative choice. One important finding in this research is that a period of discussion about the dilemma improves the levels of cooperative choice. Hopthrow and Hulbert (2005) indicate that this period of discussion also includes a cooperative group decision. However, evidence from Hopthrow?s doctoral thesis suggests that participants do not show a high ability to be able to predict and plan for a group discussion in this context. The research for this award will investigate in more detail individuals beliefs about group discussion and their effect on actual group discussions/decisions in an environmental context. Participants will be asked to play an environmental dilemma in groups of 5 people. The impact of meta-cognitive knowledge of discussion and situational discussion variables on cooperative choice will be measured.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2008-08-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2007-09-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>55811</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>Interviewed for Radio Show 